ies brings together thirty-five Asian American and Pacific Islander authors in a single volume to explore the historical experiences, perspectives, and actions of Asian American and Pacific Islander women in the United States and beyond. This volume is unique in exploring Asian American and Pacific Islander women’s lives along local, transnational, and global dimensions. The contributions present new research on diverse aspects of Asian American and Pacific Islander women’s history, from the politics of language, to the role of food, to experiences as adoptees, mixed race, and second generation, while acknowledging shared experiences as women of color in the United States. Our Voices, Our Histories showcases how new approaches in US history, Asian American and Pacific Islander studies, and Women’s and Gender studies inform research on Asian American and Pacific Islander women. Attending to the collective voices of the women themselves, the volume seeks to transform current understandings of Asian American and Pacific Islander women’s histories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAsian American womenvBiography. 0aAsian American womenxHistory. 0aAsian American womenxSocial conditions. 0aPacific Islander American womenvBiography. 0aPacific Islander American womenxHistory. 0aPacific Islander American womenxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh  a1.5 generation.  a1982 New York City’s garment workers’ strike.  aAdoptees.  aAngel Island Immigration Station Chinese Exclusion Act (1882).  aAsian American dance.  aAsian Americans in the U.S. South.  aAsian Migration.  aAssimilation.  aChinatown Night Clubs.  aChinese immigrant women.  aChinese missions in the U.S. South.  aCivil Liberties Act of 1988.  aCoolie.  aCreation Narratives.  aDancie Yett Wong.  aD